My plan for the next 1.5 weeks (for the mini-presentation on April 8), is as follows:
Explain in detail how the Shillito paper models SFQ kicks using a pulse train with appropriate examples
Explain how the paper implements a SFQ DRAG analog using on/off ramp unitaries encoded as binary strings
Explain how the paper defines fidelity metrics and decomposes a target unitary into a linear combination of I, pauli_x, pauli_y, pauli_z for error analysis (they also do model deviations in anharmonicity, qubit frequency, time jitter, the kick angle, and the qubit decay rate "gamma", although it will take me time to model how these affect the fidelity of the target unitary, for example I do not yet know what "time jitter" is at this point)
Work through the math n=4 (trivial single qubit) Grover Search using the Shillito framework
Figure out a gate set for Grover's search
Simulate the n=4 case in my code (this will require me to augment my current simulator to work for two qubits instead of the single qubit simulator I have at the moment, might be harder than I anticipate)